Output:
# ADR 0007: Define the Config and Environment Boundary

## Status

Accepted

## Context

Rhapsody has three kinds of configuration pressure:

- deployment secrets and infrastructure settings such as admin auth, Turso, GitHub, mediator, Cron,
  webhook, Vercel, and Codex credential state;
- instance-level project settings that tell one Rhapsody deployment which GitHub ProjectV2 board
  and repository it owns for the MVP;
- repository-owned workflow policy such as the agent command, prompts, hooks, handoff behavior, and
  sandbox/runtime preferences.

Mixing these into one source would either put secrets near repository workflow files, make
per-repository workflow policy hard to version, or make future multi-project support harder to add.
Rhapsody needs a clear boundary before implementing the config loader, scheduler, tracker client,
mediators, and runner workflows.

## Decision

Use a layered configuration model:

1. Deployment environment variables for instance-level secrets, credentials, and infrastructure.
2. A typed Rhapsody project config for the MVP's single configured GitHub Project/repository.
3. A repository workflow file, `RHAPSODY.md` with fallback to `WORKFLOW.md`, for per-repository
   agent behavior and runtime policy.

The MVP may load the typed project config from environment variables first. The TypeScript config
shape must still model it as a singleton project object so it can later become an array of project
objects without changing scheduler, tracker, or dashboard call sites materially.

Repository workflow files must not contain raw secrets. They may reference secrets only through
explicitly supported `$VAR` indirection fields. Rhapsody resolves those references in the trusted
control plane before configuring mediators, sandbox network policy, or runner commands.

Production configuration must fail closed for dispatch-critical missing values. Local development may
allow narrowly scoped defaults when they do not grant access, start external work, or weaken secret
handling.

## Configuration Ownership

Deployment environment variables own:

- admin authentication and machine trigger secrets;
- durable store location and credentials;
- upstream GitHub credentials held by the trusted host;
- mediator shared secrets and trusted token state;
- Vercel credentials needed by the Sandbox SDK or deployment integration;
- feature switches that determine whether Cron, webhook, or brokered auth paths are enabled.

Rhapsody project config owns:

- the configured GitHub ProjectV2 owner, repository, project number, status field, and status sets;
- scheduler limits and claim TTLs;
- default Git branch and branch prefix;
- default sandbox runtime and workspace constraints;
- default agent command and turn limits;
- mediator mode and write policy.

Repository workflow files own:

- per-repository prompt template;
- per-repository agent command override when allowed by project config;
- hooks that run inside the sandbox workspace;
- workflow retry policy and fatal error classes;
- handoff and post-run policy that is safe to version with the repository.

## MVP Environment Variables

| Env var | Required | Secret | Purpose | Local development behavior |
|---|---:|---:|---|---|
| `ROOT_PASSWORD` | production yes | yes | Admin login password | May be omitted only if admin UI is disabled |
| `AUTH_SECRET` | production yes | yes | Session cookie signing | May use generated dev-only value |
| `TURSO_DATABASE_URL` | yes | no-ish | libSQL state store URL | May point to local libSQL file/server |
| `TURSO_AUTH_TOKEN` | hosted Turso yes | yes | libSQL state store auth | May be omitted for local unauthenticated DB |
| `GITHUB_TOKEN` | yes | yes | Upstream GitHub PAT held by trusted host | Required before tracker or mediator calls |
| `MEDIATOR_SECRET` | yes | yes | Sandbox-to-mediator shared secret | Required before runner dispatch |
| `CRON_SECRET` | if Cron enabled | yes | Vercel Cron endpoint auth | May be omitted when Cron route is disabled |
| `GITHUB_WEBHOOK_SECRET` | if webhooks enabled | yes | GitHub webhook signature verification | May be omitted when webhooks are disabled |
| `CHATGPT_ACCESS_TOKEN` and token state vars | if brokered Codex auth enabled | yes | Trusted ChatGPT/Codex credential state | Required before Codex runner dispatch |
| `VERCEL_TOKEN` | if SDK/runtime requires it | yes | Vercel API/Sandbox management | May be omitted when ambient Vercel auth works |
| `VERCEL_TEAM_ID` | if SDK/runtime requires it | mixed | Vercel team scope | Optional unless explicit API calls need it |
| `VERCEL_PROJECT_ID` | if SDK/runtime requires it | no | Vercel project scope | Optional unless explicit API calls need it |
| `RHAPSODY_PROJECT_OWNER` | yes | no | GitHub owner or organization for the MVP project | Required before scheduling |
| `RHAPSODY_PROJECT_REPOSITORY` | yes | no | Target repository name for the MVP | Required before scheduling |
| `RHAPSODY_PROJECT_NUMBER` | yes | no | GitHub ProjectV2 number | Required before scheduling |
| `RHAPSODY_STATUS_FIELD` | no | no | ProjectV2 status field name | Defaults to `Status` |
| `RHAPSODY_ACTIVE_STATUSES` | no | no | Comma-separated dispatchable statuses | Defaults to `Todo,In Progress` |
| `RHAPSODY_TERMINAL_STATUSES` | no | no | Comma-separated terminal statuses | Defaults to `Done,Canceled,Cancelled,Duplicate` |
| `RHAPSODY_HANDOFF_STATUS` | no | no | Optional status after successful handoff | Omitted by default |

`no-ish` means the value is not a credential by itself but may reveal deployment topology and should
not be printed casually in logs.

## Initial Typed Config Shape

```ts
type RhapsodyConfig = {
  env: {
    nodeEnv: "development" | "test" | "production";
    cronEnabled: boolean;
    webhookEnabled: boolean;
    brokeredCodexAuthEnabled: boolean;
  };
  project: RhapsodyProjectConfig;
};

type RhapsodyProjectConfig = {
  tracker: {
    kind: "github_project";
    owner: string;
    repository: string;
    projectNumber: number;
    projectId?: string;
    statusField: string;
    activeStatuses: string[];
    terminalStatuses: string[];
    handoffStatus?: string;
  };
  github: {
    defaultBranch: string;
    branchPrefix: string;
    openPullRequest: boolean;
    writeMode: "agent_mediated";
  };
  scheduler: {
    maxConcurrentRuns: number;
    maxConcurrentRunsByStatus: Record<string, number>;
    claimTtlMs: number;
    maxRetryBackoffMs: number;
  };
  sandbox: {
    runtime: "node24" | string;
    workspacePath: string;
    source: "git" | "snapshot";
    networkPolicy: "default_deny_with_mediators" | string;
    snapshotOnSuccess: boolean;
    snapshotOnFailure: boolean;
    maxDurationMs: number;
  };
  agent: {
    command: string;
    maxTurns: number;
    turnTimeoutMs: number;
    stallTimeoutMs: number;
    approvalPolicy: "never" | "on_request" | string;
    tools: string[];
  };
  mediators: {
    github: {
      enabled: boolean;
      secretEnv: "MEDIATOR_SECRET";
    };
    codexAuth: {
      enabled: boolean;
      secretEnv: "MEDIATOR_SECRET";
      tokenStateEnvPrefix: "CHATGPT_";
    };
  };
};
```

The config loader should expose typed getters and validation results rather than leaking raw
`process.env` access across the app. Route handlers, workflows, tracker clients, mediators, and
sandbox managers should receive typed config or a narrow config service.

## `$VAR` Indirection

`$VAR` indirection is supported only in fields that are explicitly typed as secret references or
trusted-host references. It is not a general templating language.

Supported MVP uses:

- workflow or project fields that reference host-owned credentials by name;
- mediator and sandbox policy fields that need to identify which host secret should be applied;
- future GitHub App credential references.

Unsupported MVP uses:

- interpolating arbitrary environment variables into prompts;
- passing secret values directly into sandbox environment variables by default;
- reading secrets from repository workflow files without an allowlisted field.

If a `$VAR` reference appears in an unsupported field, config validation must fail.

## Startup and Dispatch Validation

Startup validation checks whether the deployment can boot safely. Dispatch validation checks whether
Rhapsody may start scheduler or runner work.

Production startup must fail closed or disable the relevant surface when these are missing:

- `ROOT_PASSWORD` or `AUTH_SECRET` for admin UI/API access;
- `CRON_SECRET` when Cron is enabled;
- `GITHUB_WEBHOOK_SECRET` when webhooks are enabled.

Scheduler dispatch must fail before claiming work when these are missing:

- Turso URL and required auth token;
- GitHub token;
- project owner, repository, and project number;
- mediator secret;
- required Codex token state when the configured agent uses brokered Codex auth.

Runner dispatch must fail before sandbox creation when these are missing:

- sandbox runtime or Vercel credentials required by the SDK;
- agent command;
- workflow file when default workflow prompts are not explicitly enabled;
- any allowed `$VAR` reference that cannot be resolved.

## Defaults

Safe defaults:

- status field: `Status`;
- active statuses: `Todo`, `In Progress`;
- terminal statuses: `Done`, `Canceled`, `Cancelled`, `Duplicate`;
- Git default branch: `main`;
- branch prefix: `rhapsody/`;
- scheduler `maxConcurrentRuns`: `5`;
- scheduler `claimTtlMs`: `900000`;
- scheduler `maxRetryBackoffMs`: `300000`;
- sandbox runtime: `node24`;
- sandbox workspace path: `/vercel/sandbox`;
- sandbox network policy: default-deny with explicit mediator forwarding;
- `snapshotOnSuccess` and `snapshotOnFailure`: `true`;
- agent `maxTurns`: `20`;
- agent `turnTimeoutMs`: `3600000`;
- agent `stallTimeoutMs`: `300000`.

No default should silently enable unauthenticated admin access, machine triggers, GitHub writes, or
agent execution.

## Multi-Project Migration

The MVP uses one configured project:

```ts
type RhapsodyConfig = {
  project: RhapsodyProjectConfig;
};
```

The intended migration path is:

```ts
type RhapsodyConfig = {
  projects: RhapsodyProjectConfig[];
};
```

The singleton config should therefore still carry a project identity and should avoid hard-coding
global assumptions into storage keys, route shapes, event payloads, or workflow IDs. The state model
may defer a first-class project table, but run and event records should retain enough owner,
repository, ProjectV2 item, and identifier data to make later migration possible.

